The Solomon Islands has confirmed it will donate more than 250 new Toyota vehicles to its national armed forces. The vehicles, which will be supplied by Chinese manufacturers, are the latest sign of a growing relationship between the two countries, which is set to be further enhanced in coming weeks when the two nations sign the country’s first defence cooperation treaty.

Beijing’s increasing interest in the South Pacific was underscored this month with the opening of a new Chinese consulate in the Solomon Islands capital Honiara, which serves an expanding Asian superpower presence in the region.

Those arriving in Honiara are greeted by an increasingly Chinese-dominated economy, with huge new shopping malls now ringing the town.

There are Latin American-style traffic jams on Honiara’s virtually non-existent sidewalks. But what is shouldering its way to the forefront is what the Solomon Islands government hopes to provide, with its vast Chinese gifts of support.

The Solomon Islands has long enjoyed mutually supportive ties with the Australian government, dating back to when Canberra first intervened to aid peace in the tiny South Pacific nation after its independence in 1978.

But the regional dynamics have changed, with the Solomon Islands looking to Beijing in an effort to bolster its economy and product links with China that appear to be presenting a more potent offer
